ction on the rise of popular culture during the American intervention. Reexamining the war from the South Vietnamese perspective, The unimagined community pursues the provocative thesis that the conflict, in this early stage, was not an anti-communist crusade, but a struggle between two competing versions of anticolonial communism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975zVietnam, Southern. 7aHISTORY / Military / Vietnam War.2bisacsh  aCold war.  aCritical theology.  aMarxism.  aMass media.  aNationalism.  aPopular culture.  aSouth Vietnam.  aVietnam War.1 aNguyen, Duy Lap, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614397640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526143976423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526143976/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles